Jordanâ€™s trade deficit widened 10
percent in the first eight months of the year, the  Department of
Statistics  said.  The shortfall increased to 3.86 billion dinars ($5.5
billion) from 3.5 billion dinars in the same period in 2009, the
department said today in an e-mailed statement.  The cost of crude oil imports rose 30 percent, and vehicles
and motorcycles increased 20 percent, the department said. Total
imports increased 8.7 percent. Exports added 16 percent in the
first eight months as potash increased 47 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
